Project 2: Dockerize a Node.js Express Application
Goal
We want to run a Node.js application inside a Docker container instead of directly on our computer.
Without Docker
Your Computer
│
├── Node.js
├── Express
├── npm
└── Application
If another computer doesn't have Node.js installed, your app won't run.
________________________________________
With Docker
Your Computer
│
└── Docker
      │
      └── Container
            ├── Node.js
            ├── Express
            ├── npm
            └── Application
The container includes everything the application needs, so it runs consistently on any machine with Docker.
________________________________________
Step 1: Create a Project Folder
mkdir nodejs-docker-project
Explanation
•	mkdir = Make Directory 
•	Creates a new folder named nodejs-docker-project. 
Now move into the folder:
cd nodejs-docker-project
Check where you are:
pwd
Example output:
/home/ubuntu/nodejs-docker-project
Explanation
•	cd = Change Directory. 
•	pwd = Print Working Directory (shows your current location). 
________________________________________
Step 2: Initialize a Node.js Project
Create a new Node.js project:
npm init -y
What happens?
Docker doesn't need this, but Node.js does.
This command creates:
package.json
Open it:
cat package.json
Example:
{
  "name": "nodejs-docker-project",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.js"
}
What is package.json?
Think of it as the application's identity card.
It stores:
•	Project name 
•	Version 
•	Dependencies 
•	Scripts 
Without it, npm doesn't know how to manage your application.
________________________________________
Step 3: Install Express
npm install express
What happens?
npm downloads Express from the npm registry.
Now your project contains:
node_modules/
package-lock.json
package.json
What is node_modules?
It contains all the libraries required by your application.
What is package-lock.json?
It locks dependency versions so everyone installs the exact same versions.
________________________________________
Step 4: Create the Application
vi app.js
Paste:
const express = require('express');

const app = express();

const PORT = 3000;

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.send('<h1>Hello from Docker!</h1>');
});

app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server running on ${PORT}`);
});
________________________________________
Explanation Line by Line
Import Express
const express = require('express');
This loads the Express library.
________________________________________
Create the Application
const app = express();
Creates an Express application.
Think of it as starting your web server.
________________________________________
Define the Port
const PORT = 3000;
The application listens on port 3000.
________________________________________
Create a Route
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
When someone visits:
http://localhost:3000
run this function.
________________________________________
Send a Response
res.send('<h1>Hello from Docker!</h1>');
The browser displays:
Hello from Docker!
________________________________________
Start the Server
app.listen(PORT);
Starts the application.
Without this line, the application never starts.
________________________________________
Step 5: Run Without Docker
node app.js
Output:
Server running on 3000
Open:
http://localhost:3000
You should see:
Hello from Docker!
Stop it:
Ctrl + C
________________________________________
Step 6: Create the Dockerfile
Create a file named Dockerfile.
vi Dockerfile
Paste:
FROM node:20

WORKDIR /app

COPY package*.json ./

RUN npm install

COPY . .

EXPOSE 3000

CMD ["node","app.js"]
________________________________________
Dockerfile Explanation
Line 1
FROM node:20
Meaning
Start from the official Node.js 20 image.
It already includes:
•	Linux 
•	Node.js 
•	npm 
________________________________________
Line 2
WORKDIR /app
Creates the /app directory and makes it the current working directory.
Equivalent to:
mkdir /app
cd /app
inside the container.
________________________________________
Line 3
COPY package*.json ./
Copies:
package.json
package-lock.json
into the container.
We copy these first because if only your application code changes, Docker can reuse the cached dependency installation layer, making builds much faster.
________________________________________
Line 4
RUN npm install
Installs Express and other dependencies inside the Docker image.
________________________________________
Line 5
COPY . .
Copies the rest of the project files, including app.js, into the container.
________________________________________
Line 6
EXPOSE 3000
Documents that the application listens on port 3000.
It doesn't publish the port by itself; you still map it when running the container.
________________________________________
Line 7
CMD ["node","app.js"]
When the container starts, it automatically runs:
node app.js
________________________________________
Step 7: Create a .dockerignore
vi .dockerignore
Contents:
node_modules
Why?
When Docker copies the project:
COPY . .
it would otherwise copy your local node_modules.
Instead, Docker installs fresh dependencies inside the image, keeping the image cleaner and avoiding platform-specific issues.
________________________________________
Step 8: Build the Image
docker build -t node-app .
Explanation
docker build
Build a Docker image.
-t
Assign a name.
node-app
Image name.
.
Use the current directory as the build context.
________________________________________
Check the image:
docker images
Output:
REPOSITORY    TAG
node-app      latest
________________________________________
Step 9: Run the Container
docker run -d -p 3000:3000 --name node-container node-app
Explanation
docker run
Creates and starts a container.
-d
Runs it in the background (detached mode).
-p 3000:3000
Maps:
Computer Port → Container Port

3000      →      3000
--name
Gives the container a friendly name.
node-app
The image to use.
________________________________________
Step 10: Verify
docker ps
Example:
CONTAINER ID    IMAGE
8ab76d          node-app
________________________________________
Step 11: Test
Open:
http://localhost:3000
You'll see:
Hello from Docker!
________________________________________
Step 12: Check Logs
docker logs node-container
Output:
Server running on 3000
________________________________________
Step 13: Enter the Container
docker exec -it node-container /bin/bash
Inside the container:
pwd
Output:
/app
List files:
ls
View your application:
cat app.js
Exit:
exit
________________________________________
Step 14: Stop and Remove
Stop:
docker stop node-container
Remove:
docker rm node-container
Delete the image:
docker rmi node-app
